When the algorithm starts, it assumes the first element (2) is the majority and increases the count as long as it keeps seeing the same element.
However, whenever a different element appears, the count decreases because it represents a “cancellation” of support.
In the array `[2,2,1,1,3,3,3]`, the two 1’s cancel out the two 2’s, bringing the count back to 0.
This is the most important moment: when the count becomes 0, the algorithm “forgets” the previous candidate (2) because it no longer has any support.
From that point, the next element (3) is treated as a fresh candidate, and since the remaining elements are all 3, the count keeps increasing.
This is how the algorithm eventually reaches 3 as the final candidate.
